U.S.- CHINA | ECONOMIC and SECURITY REVIEW COMMISSION

U.S.-China Economic AND Security Review Commission

  • About Us
    About the Commission

    The U.S.-China Economic and Security Review Commission is a legislative branch commission created by the United States Congress in October 2000 with the legislative mandate to monitor, investigate, and submit to Congress an annual report on the national security implications of the bilateral trade and economic relationship between the United States and the Peopleâ€™s Republic of China, and to provide recommendations, where appropriate, to Congress for legislative and administrative action.

    Research

    The U.S.-China Economic and Security Review Commission is chartered to monitor, investigate, and report to Congress on the national security implications of the bilateral trade and economic relationship between the United States and the Peopleâ€™s Republic of China. The Commission meets its research mission by submitting to Congress an Annual Report, as well as by conducting staff-led reports, contracted research, and more.

Body

Chinaâ€™s Position on Russiaâ€™s Invasion of Ukraine

Key Events and Statements from February 21, 2022 through August 31, 2025

Below is a list of key actions and statements summarizing Chinaâ€™s official position on Russiaâ€™s unprovoked invasion of Ukraine, which began on February 24, 2022. Items highlighted include Chinaâ€™s official government statements, press conferences, messages to the international community, media publications, and where available, leaked internal Chinese Communist Party (CCP) guidance for media and propaganda outlets.

(For a Timeline of key events in the lead up to the February 21, 2022, Russian invasion of Ukraine, visit https://www.uscc.gov/research/china-russia-interactions-leading-invasion-ukraine)

Entries are organized into the following categories:

  • [Action]: Chinese government activity which impacts the conflict in Ukraine
  • [Sanctions]: Chinese efforts to undermine international sanctions on Russia
  • [Statement]: Statements by Chinese government officials on the Ukraine conflict
  • [Media]: Chinese media stories reflecting official positions and censorship guidelines
  • [Event]: Major international events involving China, Russia, and Ukraine

[Timeline in reverse order, most recent event on top]

August 29, 2025

  • [Statement] When asked about Russiaâ€™s recent strikes on Kyiv that killed more than 20 people, Chinaâ€™s Foreign Ministry Spokesperson Guo Jiakun does not directly condemn the strikes, but reiterates Chinaâ€™s â€œthree principles of no expansion of the battlefield, no escalation of the fighting, and no party adding fuel to the flames.â€

August 28, 2025

  • [Sanctions] For the first time, a tanker carrying liquified natural gas from the U.S.-sanctioned Arctic LNG 2 plant in Russia docked at a Chinese terminal.

August 25, 2025

  • [Statement] For the first time since Russiaâ€™s invasion of Ukraine, General Secretary of the CCP Xi Jinping sends a congratulatory message to Ukraineâ€™s President Volodymyr Zelenskyy on Ukraineâ€™s Independence Day. While Zelenskyy posted Xiâ€™s message on social media, Chinaâ€™s Ministry of Foreign Affairs declined to confirm whether Xi had sent the message. 

August 20, 2025

  • [Statement] Ukraineâ€™s President Volodymyr Zelenskyy states that he does not consider China to be a potential security guarantor for a peace deal with Russia due to Chinaâ€™s lack of support for Ukraine and its ongoing supply of drones to Russia. In response, Chinaâ€™s Foreign Ministry Spokesperson Mao Ning says that China remains willing to play a â€œconstructive roleâ€ in promoting a resolution to the war. 

August 13, 2025

  • [Action] In response to new EU sanctions on two Chinese banks for providing â€œcrypto asset servicesâ€ to Russia, Chinaâ€™s Ministry of Commerce announces retaliatory sanctions on two Lithuanian banks, UAB Urbo Bankas and AB Mano Bankas.  

August 8, 2025

  • [Sanctions] In response to comments by U.S. President Donald Trump that the United States could impose additional tariffs on China for purchasing sanctioned Russian oil, Chinaâ€™s Foreign Ministry Spokesperson Guo Jiakun says that all of Chinaâ€™s trade with Russia is â€œlegitimate and legal.â€
  • [Statement] During a call with General Secretary of the CCP Xi Jinping, Russiaâ€™s President Vladimir Putin shares Russiaâ€™s views on the current state of the Ukraine crisis and recent discussions with the United States. Xi says that China is pleased to see ongoing U.S.-Russia communication and efforts to promote a political settlement of the Ukraine crisis. 

August 6, 2025

  • [Statement] In a call with Chief Advisor to the President of Brazil Celso Amorim, Chinaâ€™s Foreign Minister Wang Yi states that discussions on ending Russiaâ€™s war in Ukraine are at a critical moment. Wang Yi further says that China and Brazil can continue playing a role in promoting a political resolution to the crisis and building consensus among â€œGlobal Southâ€ countries in favor of a ceasefire.

July 27, 2025

  • [Sanctions] Ukraineâ€™s President Volodymyr Zelenskyy sanctions 53 individuals and entities accused of supporting Russiaâ€™s defense industry, including some Chinese nationals and companies. Chinaâ€™s Foreign Ministry Spokesperson Guo Jiakun criticizes the sanctions and urges Ukraine to â€œcorrect its mistake immediately.â€ 

July 25, 2025

  • [Event] The UN Security Council holds a briefing during which the U.S. and Chinese representatives exchange recriminations regarding Russiaâ€™s war in Ukraine. Acting U.S. Representative to the UN Dorothy Shea urges China to stop providing Russia with dual-use goods that enable its drone and missile attacks in Ukraine. In response, Chinaâ€™s Deputy Ambassador to the UN Geng Shuang criticizes the United States for â€œspreading liesâ€ about China and â€œcreating divisionsâ€ on the Ukraine issue.

July 23, 2025

  • [Sanctions] According to Reuters, Chinese companies are covertly shipping engines to Russian state-owned weapons manufacturer IEMZ Kupol by falsely labeling them as â€œindustrial refrigeration unitsâ€ to evade Western sanctions. These shipments have enabled IEMZ Kupol to increase production of its Garpiya-A1 attack drone, which has been used to attack military and civilian targets in Ukraine.

July 13, 2025

  • [Statement] On the sidelines of the Shanghai Cooperation Organization meeting in Beijing, Chinaâ€™s Foreign Minister Wang Yi meets with Russiaâ€™s Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov to exchange views on the war in Ukraine, among other issues.

July 9, 2025

  • [Action] The Security Service of Ukraine arrests two Chinese nationals, a father and son, for allegedly spying on Ukraineâ€™s Neptune anti-ship missile program, which is critical to Ukraineâ€™s coastal defense against the Russian navy. Chinaâ€™s Foreign Ministry Spokesperson Mao Ning states that China is â€œstill confirming the relevant informationâ€ and will â€œprotect the legal rights and interests of Chinese citizens.â€

July 2, 2025

  • [Statement] Chinaâ€™s Foreign Minister Wang Yi tells European Union officials that Beijing does not want a Russian loss in Ukraine because the United States might then shift its entire focus toward China. In a subsequent press conference, Chinaâ€™s Foreign Ministry Spokesperson Mao Ning states that a prolonged conflict in Ukraine is not in any partyâ€™s interests.
